The Straits Times and the National Library Board you ask, we answer, come listen How to stay sane in the Covid-19 economic downturn Joyce Teo The Straits Times’ senior health correspond­ent hosts a mindfulnes­s expert and founder of the Brahm Centre, a charity where people can get health education as well as emotional and mental support. She was named The Straits Times Singaporea­n of The Year 2019 for her advocacy of mental wellness. Ms Angie Chew, The Covid-19 pandemic has severely impacted the Singapore economy, and, in the coming months, business closures, retrenchme­nts and unemployme­nt are expected to go up.
offers insights on how you can reframe your thinking to prepare yourself for the changes that may come in this pandemic, and emerge stronger, more resilient and more positive. Ms Chew Have a question on mental health for them? str.sg/askstSEP Send it to by Sept 15, 7pm Selected questions will be addressed by the speakers and included in the video Joyce Teo Angie Chew Senior Health Correspond­ent The Straits Times Founder Brahm Centre Mark your calendar and watch the video Friday, Sept 25, 7pm The Straits Times Facebook PRINTED AND DISTRIBUTE­D BY PRESSREADE­R PressReade­r.com +1 604 278 4604 ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY COPYRIGHT AND PROTECTED BY APPLICABLE LAW
